The right-wing populists in Austria have won 29% of the vote.
A marked weakening of both sides of the previous grand coalition and a significant strengthening of the right-wing populist parties have, according to the first preliminary results, brought the early parliamentary elections in Austria on Sunday.
The Austrian People's Party (ÖVP) suffered particularly heavy losses, with the position of current chairman Wilhelm Molterer being seriously shaken.
On the other hand, the electoral leader of the Bund for the Future of Austria (BZÖ), the Korut-based Heitman Jörg Haider, is preparing a triumphant return to national politics.
According to preliminary results, the Social Democracy (SPÖ) remains the strongest party in the country with 29.8 percent of the vote, but it is losing 5.5 percent of the vote compared to the last election in 2006.
The ÖVP, which is losing almost nine percent of the vote, has suffered an even worse loss with 25.6 percent.
It's the worst result of both these major parties in post-war Austrian history and especially for the Luddites who called the early election, a disastrous result.
In early July, when the ÖVP withdrew from the coalition, the populists had a considerable lead in preferences over the SPÖ.
But the voters clearly punished them for letting the government fail.
Already in the first reactions to the results, speculation was voiced about the possible resignation of the party chairman and former vice-chancellor Wilhelm Molterer.
Observers believe that this could happen as early as Monday at the extraordinary meeting of the party's leadership.
Such a development would probably pave the way for the still most likely outcome of the election result, namely the renewal of the SPÖ and ÖVP grand coalition.
With the strengthening of the right wing of the two populist parties - the Freedom Party (FPÖ) gaining 18 percent and the BZÖ 11 percent of the vote - the Social Democrats also expressed their fear of a repeat of 1999, when the populists and the populists (at that time the FPÖ were still united, but in 2005 they split from the BZÖ) agreed on a joint government, which even provoked sanctions from the European Union.
This is clearly the case with Haider, who has already declared his readiness to cooperate with any party and envisages a return to Vienna to the national policy.
The Green Party also entered parliament, but lost easily and fell from third to fifth place among Austria's political parties.
None of the other parties clearly crossed the four percent threshold and entered Parliament.
