Turkish diplomatic horizons are expanding
Long before Turkey began to seek membership in the European Union, European powers were eager to penetrate deep into Turkish territory.
On the eastern shore of the Bosporus, perhaps only twenty paces from Asia, stands one of the finest monuments to this unsuccessful imperial ambition.
Hydarpaşa railway station was designed by two German architects Otto Ritter and Helmut Konu in a Neo-Renaissance style.
I mean, that's what the tour guides tell you.
The building sits perpendicular to the end of the platform with towers at each corner of the facade, overlooking the unrecognizable view from some provincial German town hall.
The stone is dirty.
The whole building is falling apart.
But once you get inside the vaulted treasury, you can no longer doubt the size of the establishment whose westernmost gateway was the station.
The station was opened in August 1908 by the German consortium Anatolian-Baghdad Corporation.
Germany, a latecomer to the imperial game, was intent on realizing its ambitions to dominate the Middle East by means of this railway, which was to lead to Damascus, Baghdad and on to what is now Saudi Arabia.
But German imperial ambitions collapsed during World War I.
Their railroads were attacked by Lawrence of Arabia and his irregular troops.
The relative isolation from the surrounding territories, created by the frozen borders of the Cold War, is gone.
British and colonial troops advanced from Egypt and drove the Turks and their German allies out of Palestine and Syria.
And for Hydarpasa station, there was bad news too.
In 1917, an explosion on an ammunition train destroyed its elaborate roof.
Turkish sources say it was sabotage.
Since then, it has been gradually drilled and history has bypassed it.
But today, this gateway to Anatolia and beyond serves - at least symbolically - to highlight the expanding horizons of Turkish diplomacy.
The ruling Justice and Development Party (AKP) has created a completely new foreign policy for the country.
The relative isolation from surrounding territories created by the frozen borders of the Cold War is gone.
Now the new policy applies - Turkey is involved.
It is remarkable that the Turkish government has good relations with Israel and Syria, with the Palestinian factions Hamas and Fatah, with Iraq and Iran and of course with the European Union and the United States.
To review the parameters of this new policy, I took the night train to the Turkish capital Ankara, where I was to meet one of the AKP's leading experts on foreign policy, Turkish MP Suat Kiniklioglu.
The next morning - about ten and a half hours later - after a whirlwind ride on tracks that resembled the old-world rhythms of the famous documentary The Night's Mail, I arrived in the Turkish metropolis, designed as a new city for a secular state that wants to turn its back on its Ottoman past.
However, with its well-known Islamist roots, the AKP represents a paradigm shift in the Turkish consensus.
She's aroused suspicion in the West, especially in Washington.
The taxi took me to the AKP headquarters, an ultra-modern stone and metal building, deliberately built on a developing suburb, surrounded by half-built shophouses and power-hauling shops, where middle managers in business suits - men and women - meet to do their early morning business.
Suat Kiniklioglu could easily be a centre-right politician from almost any other European political party.
Jacket, tie, I'm sure he had a Blackberry.
"The aim of the party's foreign policy is to reintegrate Turkey into its immediate neighbourhood.
The Cold War was an anomaly", he told me.
Turkey has been cut off from its perimeter.
Today, he must look east and west at the same time.
It was no choice.
It had to do both.
"But there will surely come a time", I asked, "when Turkey may have to make a decision?"
"Turkey", he said, "you didn't want to have to make that decision".
He then emphasized what almost everyone I spoke to here said almost by heart: that Turkey's relations not only with the Middle East, but also with the Caucasus and the Black Sea region are as much in Europe's and the United States' interests as Turkey's.
With Turkey on board, it seems that Europe as a whole can, metaphorically speaking, go east on these tracks to Asia and the Middle East.
Back at the Hydarpasa station, after another mostly sleepless night, I thought of the two German gentlemen, Herr Ritter and Herr Con, who had watched this building being built a hundred years ago.
How surprised they would be to find that European ambitions in the Middle East may now be, in substantial part, in Turkish hands.
And as I was waiting in the harbor for the ferry back across the Bosphorus, I remembered that in those days, Turkey was called the "sick man of Europe".
So it seems that at least back then there wasn't much doubt as to which continent should claim this fascinating land.
