How many times did Tod tell us to "let the music speak for itself".
He said, "The composer knows what he wants.
It's all in the music.
Then sing it!"
His drumming was perfectly clear and precise, but it was neither dictatorial nor flowery.
Wherever the standard of music was, he always raised it.
John Frayn Turner writes:
If any conductor should be knighted, it was Vernon Handley.
I knew him well in the two decades he conducted the Guildford Philharmonic from 1962 to 1982.
Over the past 40 years or so, I have reviewed more than 100 of his concerts, and I can honestly say that I have never been disappointed by any of them - and I have been inspired by many.
Todd Handley had such a wonderful combination of greatness and personal modesty.
He hated conductors who, in his words, simply "pull one or two dirty pegs around the world".
He will be missed by many of us.
