The "bee car" prevents the collision
To advance the development of crash-prevention technologies, Nissan took inspiration from nature, specifically bees.
This Japanese company has developed a robot that mimics the flight pattern of bees to prevent collisions.
This is the Bio-Mimetic Car Robot Drive, or BR23C, which represents the first step in crash prevention technology.
Engineers at the Nissan Motor Co. Center for Advanced Technology have developed the robot in collaboration with the Center for Advanced Research in Science and Technology at Japan's prestigious University of Tokyo.
According to Kazuhiro Doie, general director of public relations for the brand's technology, research and development, the BR23C is presented as an extension of the four zones of the Nissan safety shield.
The robot is designed to enhance the collision-prevention capability of the vehicles.
During flight, each bee creates its own personal oval-shaped space, very similar to a Nissan safety shield.
Most important, though, are the bee's compound eyes, which are able to see in all directions at an angle of more than 300 degrees, allowing the bee to fly in its own personal space without stopping.
In creating this visual feature, the engineers designed what they called a laser rangefinder.
It records obstacles up to two metres in the 180 degree radius before the BR23C, calculates the distance to the object and sends a signal to the on-board microprocessor, which immediately translates it into a collision warning.
"Once an obstacle is detected, the robot mimics the bee's movements and immediately changes direction by turning the wheel at a right or even a right angle to avoid collision.
The biggest difference from any existing system is the fact that all the evasive maneuvers are completely instinctive.
If this were not the case, the robot would not be able to react quickly enough to avoid obstacles", explains Toshiyuki Andoh, Director of the Mobile Lab and the project's chief engineer.
Unlike bees, a robot cannot move up and down or diagonally, its movement is limited to two dimensions and the direction that its wheels allow it to move, but not in the infinite number of directions and possibilities of a bee.
So, in addition to accelerating and decelerating, Nissan also used a rotation function to prevent the robot from colliding.
"The device only needs every few seconds to process the information and act on it.
It requires no memory or logical intuition from previous maneuvers, which allows it to operate without interruption with only two dozen kilobytes of memory.
It may surprise you, but we're not talking about gigabytes or mega-gigabytes in memory".
This is the first step in the development of a new technology called instant collision avoidance, a technology that Nissan predicts will be used in production cars within a decade.
The robot uses lithium polymer batteries that are lighter and last longer than lithium-ion batteries.
Another possible future use of this technology could be to incorporate a unit into the GPS satellite navigation system to guide the driver to the destination while avoiding obstacles in the road.
