Rafael Correa is in Quito on Monday.
To re-establish the Republic around 21st century socialism.
This is the joint project of Venezuelan Hugo Chavez, Bolivian Eva Morales and Ecuadorian Rafael Correy.
Last Sunday, the third nominee put to a vote, following the example of his counterparts and friends, a draft of a new Constitution.
And his mission is accomplished, because 64% of the voters, according to official results covering 80% of the vote, voted "yes" in the referendum.
According to these results, "No" received 28%, 7% of the votes were invalid and 0.7% of ballots were blank.
For the Constitution to be adopted, he had to get half the votes plus one.
Two exit polls and a poll by a non-governmental organization predicted a clear "yes" victory on Sunday, with a range of 63% to 70%.
Rafael Correa last night, from Sunday to Monday, claimed victory for his draft constitution.
"The Constitution has won on all fronts", he said congratulating the Ecuadorians at the Guayaquil governorate, 280 kilometers southwest of Quito.
It goes without saying that Rafael Correa has received congratulatory messages from Chávez and Morales, but also from his Chilean counterpart, Michelle Bachelet.
The vote, which was held in a calm manner according to the OAS observation mission, was on the text of 444 points that build the "new socialism" promoted by the president.
The draft Constitution confers economic power on the state by reserving to it the "planning of development" of a country that lives primarily on oil extraction by foreign companies and on the foreign currency sent by its emigrants.
The Correia-backed bill, which was passed in 2006, also expands the powers of the head of state, who will be able to serve two consecutive four-year terms and will have the ability to dissolve the House.
Correa has already announced that he will use this power and will seek a new mandate in February 2009.
The constitution, among other things, enshrines the principle of free health care and education, which the president has begun to implement in a country of 13.9 million people, where 50% of the population lives below the poverty line.
Finally, it also includes a ban on the presence of foreign troops, ending an agreement between Washington and Quito on the use of an Ecuadorian base as a base for U.S. counter-narcotics operations.
19 hostages freed in Chad
An Egyptian commando has kidnapped 11 tourists and their eight-member entourage, who were taken hostage ten days ago.
They're in Cairo.
Eleven European tourists and their eight Egyptian escorts, who had been held captive in the desert for ten days, were safely transported to the Egyptian capital on Monday.
They were freed by Egyptian commandos in Chad during the morning.
The hostages arrived at about 3:30 p.m., apparently in good shape, aboard a special plane to the al-Maza military base, which is adjacent to Cairo International Airport.
They were immediately taken, without a chance to speak to the press, by helicopter to a hospital in Maadi, a suburb of Cairo, for medical examinations.
"They are completely healthy" and "no ransom was paid to the hostages", said Tourism Minister Zoheir Garrana on the runway.
Since their capture on September 19 during a four-wheel drive safari at the foot of Mount Uanat, on the borders of Egypt, Sudan and Libya, a group of hostages have been dragged from one hideout to another by 35 unknown kidnappers.
The group includes 11 tourists - five Italians, five Germans and one Romanian - as well as eight Egyptians: two guides, four drivers, a border guard and the director of the Aegyptous agency, the safari organiser.
A senior Egyptian security official indicated that 30 members of the special forces, who had approached the site in two helicopters, had taken off during the night just before dawn.
"There was a shootout, half of the kidnappers were killed and the rest fled", said the source, who wished to remain anonymous.
He noted that a total of 150 members of the Egyptian special forces from the Lightning unit were sent to Sudan, where they received support from German and Italian commandos.
The head of Italian diplomacy, Franco Frattini, speaking from Belgrade, where he is now, mentioned the role played by Italian special forces and secret agents.
"We must acknowledge that we have achieved this result thanks to the professionalism and efficiency of our people in the intelligence community, in the special forces", he said without elaborating.
He also denied that a ransom was paid.
On the eve of the attack, the Sudanese army said it had intercepted a four-wheel drive vehicle carrying the hijackers during a patrol, killing six of them, including the Chadian commander, and arresting two others.
The military claimed they were linked to a Darfur rebel group, the Sudan Liberation Army-Unity (SLA-U), which the movement immediately denied.
