Benelux governments to state the part of Fortis Bank
The Benelux countries will help the Belgian-Dutch bank Fortis, which was the first in Europe to fall into trouble as a result of the spillover effect of the US mortgage market, by partial nationalisation: the three countries will support the monetary and insurance institution, which also has a capital participation in Hungary, with EUR 11.2 billion.
This was agreed at the highest level this weekend by the Belgian, Luxembourg and Dutch governments, with the participation of the President of the European Central Bank and the European Competition Commissioners.
Fortis is the first bank in the euro area to have entered into a major crisis in the international financial markets, which has been spreading in waves for more than a year, and the decisions taken in this case could be considered in some respects as precedents.
Under the decision that was born on Sunday night, all three countries will buy back almost half (49 percent) of the bank's assets.
The bank will almost certainly sell some of its equity holdings, in particular the mainly insurance business acquired last year from the Dutch bank ABN Amro.
Fortis Bank's stock began to plunge sharply last week, and by the second half of the week, the institution was already showing serious signs of crisis.
But analysts agree that with 85,000 employees, the bank is too big to fail.
The company's stock fell 12 percent on Friday, to a 14-year low.
Since January, the stock has lost more than two-thirds of its value.
At current share prices, the group's total market capitalisation is around EUR 14 billion, but according to the company's executives this is unrealistic.
The management blamed the Fortis stock crash on the uncertainty in the overseas market related to the adoption of the US plan of a package worth $ 700 billion.
The stock was up a little bit on Monday.
On Friday, the bank was appointed a new CEO, Filip Dierckx.
The Mint has also been looking for private buyers, but no one has come forward with a more serious offer.
The Belgian government has previously announced that investors need not worry, they will not lose their money.
There has been no panic among the bank's clients and the branches have not been attacked.
In Hungary, Fortis has a separate branch and has also acquired several leasing companies.
The Fox in the Henhouse
Life and health insurance companies in America, based on people's purchase history, often dismiss the possibility of taking out a policy with an applicant.
Data protection experts are concerned that the data market will become uncontrollable.
'There is a data protection programme that binds the use of prescription data in any case to the consent of the person concerned.
It has to be in the hands of an independent person, or we're giving the chicken to the fox", the Washington Post quotes Richard Dick, author of the program designed to monitor prescribing.
Insurance companies make premiums and claims for accidents dependent on the health status of the person concerned and will not insure him if the risk is judged to be too great.
In the past, they would send the person to a medical examination and only contract with them if they knew the results.
A decade ago, Dick devised a much cheaper method: Using a pharmacy ID, a customer can easily see what medication he has purchased in the past year and a half, and the program itself can infer what disease he is suffering from and what his medical condition is.
For example, if he regularly buys large quantities of cholesterol-lowering drugs, this indicates that he has virtually uncontrollably high blood-fat levels, which immediately places him in the higher-risk category.
There are several versions of the program in circulation, some of which also determine the risk coefficient, so that there is almost no work left for the insurance company except for the paperwork, although minor problems arise.
The advantages of these drugs are that they can be used for many purposes, some compounds are useful for migraines and hot flashes, for example, but they are also effective against depression.
These constitute a significant risk-increasing factor from the point of view of commercial insurers, whereas the former do not.
Special companies have been set up to collect and process data, and they ask the patient's consent before obtaining the necessary information from the pharmacies.
They are now forced to do so by the authorities, even though they have not been punished for their past negligence.
Some companies have recently been incorporating lab tests into their data, which they link to drug data, providing an even more accurate picture of patients' health.
As more companies gain access to data, it will become increasingly difficult to control its use.
There is a special law on the protection of health data, but its effect is limited to health service providers and insurance companies.
A bill that would give the government the power to control companies that specialize in providing data is before Congress.
Richard Dick recognises that this is not enough: he has therefore developed his programme in such a way that the transfer of data is subject to the explicit consent of the person concerned.
The other thing is, that permission can hardly be denied, otherwise the insurance companies won't sign him.
So chickens are just a little bit too attached to the fox of good will.
The global Marseille menu
European Union and India double turnover
As the European Union and India are each other's foremost trade partners, this theme was also high on the agenda of the ninth summit, alongside other, predominantly global issues.
Today, there will also be a French-Indian summit, focusing on cooperation in the field of nuclear energy.
The European Union recognises India as a developing democratic power that should be given a greater say in international affairs, but the member states have so far failed to find common ground on supporting New Delhi's permanent membership of the UN Security Council.
The question was not even discussed further at yesterday's ninth summit in Marseille.
French President Nicolas Sarkozy, as the current President of the Union, and European Commission President José Manuel Barroso and High Representative for Foreign Affairs Javier Solana, welcomed Indian Prime Minister Manmohan Singh and agreed to double their trade turnover to more than 100 billion euros within five years.
Given that the exchange of goods increased from 25 to 55 billion between 2000 and 2007, this is not an overly ambitious target.
In a sign of this, twenty-six existing bilateral civil aviation agreements with India were legally harmonized, so that aviation also became green in the future.
India would like to sign a free trade agreement with the EU by the end of 2009.
Sarkozy promised to speed up the negotiations.
The aim is to balance the EU's trade with India, which is the EU's largest trading partner, with New Delhi ranking ninth among EU partners.
The Summit also paid attention to global issues.
The situation in Afghanistan and Pakistan, and terrorism in all its forms, were condemned by both parties and called for the urgent convening of a UN conference.
They also marked the end of the Doha round of trade negotiations, although both have contributed greatly to its failure.
The European Union has confirmed that it will stick to its energy and climate agenda, aiming to reduce its emissions by at least 20% by 2020.
India agreed, as did the climate conference next year, to reach a global agreement to reduce greenhouse gas emissions by 50 percent by 2050.
Both sides are also keen to avoid rising food prices and support the convening of an international conference to address the financial crisis.
The Prime Minister of India will arrive in the French capital today where he is set to conclude a deal on the peaceful uses of atomic energy in a bilateral meeting.
Paris believes that the contracts for the construction of the nuclear reactors in India worth 20 billion euros will be awarded to French companies.
According to the agency's reports, the deal would last for 15 years.
